## How These Roles Interact

The three roles do not operate independently — they form a working relationship that drives the RMF process from beginning to end.
```
    MyClinic – OpenMRS RMF Role Structure
    
    +---------------------------------------+
    |     Chief Information Officer (CIO)   |
    |        Authorizing Official (AO)      |
    |                                       |
    |  Reviews risk findings and makes      |
    |  the formal authorization decision    |
    +------------------+--------------------+
                       |
                       | Reviews and accepts
                       | residual risk
                       |
    +------------------v--------------------+
    |        Health IT Manager              |
    |           System Owner                |
    |                                       |
    |  Manages system lifecycle and         |
    |  coordinates security implementation  |
    +------------------+--------------------+
                       |
                       | Provides security
                       | oversight and documentation
                       |
    +------------------v--------------------+
    |       Information Security Lead       |
    |      ISSO (Security Officer)          |
    |                                       |
    |  Implements and monitors controls,    |
    |  prepares assessment documentation,   |
    |  manages findings and remediation     |
    +---------------------------------------+
```

The ISSO does the detailed security work and feeds findings up to the System Owner. The System Owner coordinates implementation and escalates risk decisions to the AO. The AO reviews the overall risk picture and makes the formal authorization decision. Information flows in both directions — the AO's risk tolerance and organizational priorities should inform the System Owner's security planning, and the ISSO's technical findings should inform the AO's authorization decision.

When this structure works well, risk management decisions are grounded in technical reality and owned at the appropriate level of organizational authority. When it breaks down — when the AO is disconnected from the actual risk picture, or when the ISSO's findings are not taken seriously by the System Owner — the framework becomes a documentation exercise rather than a genuine risk management process.

