## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the post-incident analysis of the **2014 US Office of Personnel Management breach** — which I touched on briefly on Day 11 but want to revisit through the specific lens of role clarity.

Congressional investigators found that OPM's IT security roles were poorly defined and inconsistently applied. System authorization decisions had been made without the full involvement of qualified Authorizing Officials. ISSOs had been assigned to systems without the resources or authority needed to fulfill the role effectively. The result was that the formal RMF process was producing authorization documentation without producing genuine security assurance — because the people filling the roles did not have what they needed to do the job properly.

The breach ultimately exposed the personal records of over 21 million people. The technical attack was sophisticated. But the organizational conditions that allowed it to persist undetected — unclear roles, under-resourced security staff, authorization decisions disconnected from real risk assessment — were governance failures of exactly the kind that clearly defined RMF roles are designed to prevent.

That case reinforces something I want to carry through the rest of Phase 2: the value of the RMF comes from how seriously people take their roles within it. Assigning the titles is the easy part. Building an organization where the AO actually engages with risk findings, the System Owner actually coordinates security implementation, and the ISSO actually has the resources and authority to do their job — that is the hard part, and it is the part that determines whether the framework produces real security or just documentation.

