## What I Am Still Thinking About

Something I am genuinely uncertain about for small healthcare organizations: how do you handle the independence requirement for the Security Control Assessor when the organization is too small to have separate implementation and assessment teams?

NIST acknowledges this challenge and provides some flexibility — allowing for compensating measures when full independence is not achievable. But I want to understand what those compensating measures look like in practice. Does bringing in an external consultant for the assessment fulfill the independence requirement? Does peer review within a small team count? This feels like a practical question that comes up constantly in real-world RMF implementations outside the federal government context.

